WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.240 --> 00:00:07.520
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab. This is a free,
complete course for the CCNA. If you like

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:12.379
these videos, please subscribe to follow along
with the series. Also, please like and leave

00:00:12.379 --> 00:00:17.110
a comment, and share the video to help spread
this free series of videos. Thanks for your

00:00:17.110 --> 00:00:23.490
help. Also, remember to download and use the
Anki flashcards with the link in the description,

00:00:23.490 --> 00:00:29.119
which will help you very much in remembering
what you have learned. Let’s get started.

00:00:29.119 --> 00:00:35.550
This is the 8th lecture in the series, and
part 2 on IPv4 addresses. This should be a

00:00:35.550 --> 00:00:39.830
shorter video than the last one, just covering
a few things we missed.

00:00:39.830 --> 00:00:46.750
Let’s go over what we’ll cover in this
video. I’ll do a quick review of IPv4 classes,

00:00:46.750 --> 00:00:51.431
and clarify some things I didn’t explain
well in the previous video. I’ll explain

00:00:51.431 --> 00:00:58.710
how to find... the maximum number of hosts,
the network address, the broadcast address,

00:00:58.710 --> 00:01:05.180
the first usable address, and the last usable
address of a particular network. I introduced

00:01:05.180 --> 00:01:10.399
some of these in the previous video, but its
worth explaining in more detail. Finally,

00:01:10.399 --> 00:01:16.259
I will outline how to configure IP addresses
on Cisco devices, which we’ll then practice

00:01:16.259 --> 00:01:20.579
in packet tracer, in the next video.

00:01:20.579 --> 00:01:27.140
So this is the chart of the IPv4 address classes
I showed you in the last video. I taught you

00:01:27.140 --> 00:01:32.590
that the 127 range is reserved for loopback
addresses, so its generally not considered

00:01:32.590 --> 00:01:39.380
part of the Class A range. However, the 0
range is also reserved in class A, so some

00:01:39.380 --> 00:01:47.609
might say class A really begins at 1, making
the range 1-126. Different sources say different

00:01:47.609 --> 00:01:55.130
things, so I recommend that you remember class
A as 0-127, but also keep in mind that 0 and

00:01:55.130 --> 00:02:01.929
127 are reserved, so really the usable range
is 1-126.

00:02:01.929 --> 00:02:07.729
We also saw this chart from wikipedia in the
last video. Leading bits of 0 for Class A,

00:02:07.729 --> 00:02:16.160
1 0 for class B, and 1 1 0 for Class C. A
network number bit field size, also known

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:25.050
as prefix length, of 8 for class A, 16 for
class B, and 24 for class C. a size of ‘rest

00:02:25.050 --> 00:02:31.910
bit field’ also known as the host portion
of the address, of 24 bits for class A, 16

00:02:31.910 --> 00:02:39.470
for class B, and 8 for class C. The number
of networks available in each class. and finally,

00:02:39.470 --> 00:02:44.870
the number of addresses per network. This
is the maximum number of addresses, including

00:02:44.870 --> 00:02:50.640
the network address and broadcast address.
Notice how it’s calculated. 2, to the power

00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:57.400
of 8, 16, or 24, that being the length of
the host portion. But let’s look at how

00:02:57.400 --> 00:03:01.950
to calculate the maximum number of USABLE
addresses, the number of addresses that can

00:03:01.950 --> 00:03:03.810
be assigned to hosts.

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:14.710
So, let’s take this Class C network 192.168.1.0/24.
Because it’s class C, it uses a /24 prefix

00:03:14.710 --> 00:03:21.680
length, and therefore the last octet, the
last 8 bits, are the host portion. That means

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:32.180
that the host portion can be 0 to 255. So, 0 to
255 gives us a total of 256 addresses, which

00:03:32.180 --> 00:03:38.360
is 2 to the power of 8, because there are
8 bits. But, remember those two special address

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:43.770
types I mentioned in the last video? If the
host portion is all 0s, it represents the

00:03:43.770 --> 00:03:51.141
network address, sometimes called the network
ID. It can't be assigned to a host. Also, if

00:03:51.141 --> 00:03:57.260
the host portion is all 1s, it is the network broadcast
address, the address used to send a message

00:03:57.260 --> 00:04:03.870
to all hosts on the network. It also can’t
be assigned to a host. So, actually the maximum

00:04:03.870 --> 00:04:10.560
hosts per network is 2 to the power of 8,
minus 2, which is 254 for a class C network

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:12.250
like this.

00:04:12.250 --> 00:04:23.990
Now let’s take a look at this class B network,
172.16.0.0/16, through 172.16.255.255. The

00:04:23.990 --> 00:04:32.449
host portion is 16 bits, giving 65,536 possible
addresses. However, this address with a host

00:04:32.449 --> 00:04:37.930
portion of all 0s is the network address,
and this address with a host portion of all

00:04:37.930 --> 00:04:43.270
1s is the broadcast address, so really the
maximum number of hosts in this network, or

00:04:43.270 --> 00:04:49.960
any class B network, is 65,534.

00:04:49.960 --> 00:05:00.629
Now let’s do one more example, with a class
A address. 10.0.0.0/8, through 10.255.255.255.

00:05:00.629 --> 00:05:11.880
The host portion is 24 bits, so that gives
16,777,216 possible addresses. This network

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:18.340
address and this broadcast address can’t
be assigned to hosts, however, so the maximum

00:05:18.340 --> 00:05:29.729
number of hosts in this network, or any class
A network is really 16,777,214. So, the formula

00:05:29.729 --> 00:05:37.749
for determing the number of hosts on a network
is 2 to the power of N, minus 2. N is equal

00:05:37.749 --> 00:05:41.199
to the number of host bits.

00:05:41.199 --> 00:05:49.169
Now let’s calculate the first and last usable
addresses for this class C network, 192.168.1.0/24.

00:05:49.169 --> 00:05:56.949
So, this address with a host portion of all
0s is the network address, or network ID.

00:05:56.949 --> 00:06:04.379
Add 1 by changing the last bit of the host
portion to 1 and, you get 192.168.1.1, and

00:06:04.379 --> 00:06:10.229
that is the first usable address on the network.
So, that’s how you do it. Add one to the

00:06:10.229 --> 00:06:17.691
network address to get the first usable address.
How about the last usable address? Well, this

00:06:17.691 --> 00:06:23.849
address with a host portion of all 1s is the
broadcast address. Subtract 1 from this address

00:06:23.849 --> 00:06:34.220
by switching the last bit to 0, and you get
192.168.1.254, which is the last usable address.

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:42.180
Next let’s do the same for this class B
network, 172.16.0.0/16. This address with

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:51.589
a host portion of all 0s is the network address.
Add 1 and, you get 172.16.0.1, and that is

00:06:51.589 --> 00:06:57.861
the first usable address on the network. How
about the last usable address? This address

00:06:57.861 --> 00:07:03.180
with a host portion of all 1s is the broadcast
address. Subtract 1 from this address, and

00:07:03.180 --> 00:07:11.580
you get 172.16.255.254, and that is the last
usable address.

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:18.999
Finally let’s do the same for this class
A network, 10.0.0.0/8. This address is the

00:07:18.999 --> 00:07:26.830
network address. Add 1 and, you get 10.0.0.1,
and that is the first usable address on the

00:07:26.830 --> 00:07:33.150
network. Next let’s find the last usable
address. This address with a host portion

00:07:33.150 --> 00:07:41.349
of all 1s is the broadcast address. Subtract
1, and you get 10.255.255.254,

00:07:41.349 --> 00:07:46.689
which is the last usable address. Okay, so
hopefully you understand both how to calculate

00:07:46.689 --> 00:07:52.259
the number of usable addresses in a network,
and the first and last usable address in a

00:07:52.259 --> 00:07:58.080
network. Really, we covered this material
in the last video, but I wanted to make it

00:07:58.080 --> 00:08:04.360
clear. Now let’s move on to actually configuring
a Cisco router with IP addresses!

00:08:04.360 --> 00:08:09.669
So here’s a small network I put together
in GNS3, with three small networks connected

00:08:09.669 --> 00:08:15.860
to a single router, R1. Keep in mind that
it’s not really realistic to have only a

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:21.360
single PC connected to each switch, in a real
network there would many more hosts and

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:29.069
possibly more switches in each local area
network. So, we have one class A network here,

00:08:29.069 --> 00:08:37.880
10.0.0.0/8. PC1 has the first usable address
in the network, 10.0.0.1, and we will assign

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:47.630
the last usable address, 10.255.255.254, to
R1’s gigabit0/0 interface. We have this

00:08:47.630 --> 00:08:58.910
class B network, 172.16.0.0/16. PC2 has the
first usable IP address, 172.16.0.1, and we

00:08:58.910 --> 00:09:09.370
will assign the last usable address, 172.16.255.254,
to R1’s Gigabit0/1 interface. We also have

00:09:09.370 --> 00:09:21.070
a class C network, 192.168.0.0/24. PC3 has
the first usable address, 192.168.0.1, and

00:09:21.070 --> 00:09:31.149
we will assign the last usable address, 192.168.0.254,
to R1’s Gigabit0/2 interface. Let’s go

00:09:31.149 --> 00:09:34.820
into the CLI of R1 and make the configurations.

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:42.620
So, I logged on to the CLI of R1, and as you
can see I used ‘EN’, the shortcut of the

00:09:42.620 --> 00:09:48.360
enable command, to enter privileged exec mode.
Now, let me show you a great command you can

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:54.720
use to confirm the status of each interface
on the device, as well as their IP addresses.

00:09:54.720 --> 00:10:00.360
That is the ‘show ip interface brief’
command. Let’s check out the info this command

00:10:00.360 --> 00:10:07.620
gives us. First off, the interface column
lists the network interfaces on the device.

00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:17.130
As you can see, this router has four interfaces,
gigabiterthernet 0/0, 0/1, 0/2, and 0/3. The

00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:22.750
next column lists the IP address of each interface.
As you can see, they are all unassigned at

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:28.450
the moment, but we will soon assign IP addresses
to the top three interfaces. We’ll use this

00:10:28.450 --> 00:10:35.260
command again afterward to check. Next is
the ‘OK?’ column. I think this is a legacy

00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:41.500
feature of the command, its not relevant anymore.
Basically, it says whether or not the IP address

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:48.060
is valid or not. On modern devices, the device
won’t let you assign invalid IP addresses,

00:10:48.060 --> 00:10:54.440
so you should never see ‘NO’ in this column.
The interfaces currently have no IP addresses

00:10:54.440 --> 00:11:01.390
assigned, and as you can see, that is considered
a valid state. Next is the method column.

00:11:01.390 --> 00:11:06.740
This indicates the method by which the interface
was assigned an IP address. Currently the

00:11:06.740 --> 00:11:13.450
status is unset, but let’s check what it
is after we assign IP addresses. Next is the

00:11:13.450 --> 00:11:20.550
status column. Basically, you can consider
this the Layer 1 status of the interface.

00:11:20.550 --> 00:11:25.730
If the interface is enabled, there is a cable
connected, and the other end of the cable

00:11:25.730 --> 00:11:31.209
is properly connected to another device, you
should see ‘up’ here. However, here it

00:11:31.209 --> 00:11:36.790
displays ‘administratively down’. This
means the interface has been disabled with

00:11:36.790 --> 00:11:42.990
the ‘shutdown’ command. However, I haven’t
done any configuration on the interfaces yet.

00:11:42.990 --> 00:11:49.220
So, this is the default status of Cisco router
interfaces. We haven’t looked at switch

00:11:49.220 --> 00:11:56.050
interfaces yet, but Cisco switch interfaces
are NOT administratively down by default.

00:11:56.050 --> 00:12:01.370
They will either be up, if they are connected
to another device, or down, if they are not

00:12:01.370 --> 00:12:08.509
connected. Notice that, even though gigabit
ethernet 0/0, 0/1, and 0/2 on this router

00:12:08.509 --> 00:12:14.240
are connected to switches, the interfaces
remain administratively down because the ‘shutdown’

00:12:14.240 --> 00:12:20.389
command is applied to them by default. The
final field of the output is ‘protocol’.

00:12:20.389 --> 00:12:26.089
While the ‘status’ column referred to
the Layer 1 status of the interface, this

00:12:26.089 --> 00:12:33.490
is the Layer 2 status. Because the interfaces
are down at Layer 1, layer 2 cant operate,

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:38.540
so all of these interfaces are down at Layer
2. You’ll never see an interface with a

00:12:38.540 --> 00:12:44.040
‘down’ in the status column and ‘up’
in the protocol column, although the reverse

00:12:44.040 --> 00:12:50.810
is possible. Once we configure these interfaces
and enable them, we should see up in both

00:12:50.810 --> 00:12:57.060
the status and protocol columns. So, remember
these points, the ‘status’ column refers

00:12:57.060 --> 00:13:04.980
to the Layer 1 status, for example is the interface
shutdown, is there a cable attached, etc.

00:13:04.980 --> 00:13:10.640
The protocol column refers to the layer 2
status, for example is Ethernet functioning properly

00:13:10.640 --> 00:13:16.980
between this device and the device it's connected
to. Expect both of these columns to show up

00:13:16.980 --> 00:13:19.550
once we’re finished with our configurations!

00:13:19.550 --> 00:13:27.379
So, let’s configure the gigabitethernet0/0
interface first. I use conf t, the shortcut

00:13:27.379 --> 00:13:33.110
of the ‘configure terminal’ command to
enter global config mode. Next, to configure

00:13:33.110 --> 00:13:40.230
the interface itself, I have to enter interface
config mode. So, I use the command ‘interface’,

00:13:40.230 --> 00:13:48.519
followed by the name of the interface, gigabitethernet
0/0. As you can see, it now displays config-if

00:13:48.519 --> 00:13:54.329
beside the hostname of the device. Now, before
we move on, let me show you some other ways

00:13:54.329 --> 00:14:00.149
to enter interface configuration mode. First
off, notice that you don’t need the space

00:14:00.149 --> 00:14:06.810
between ‘gigabitethernet’ and 0/0, you
can connect them and the CLI will still understand

00:14:06.810 --> 00:14:13.639
and bring you to interface configuration mode
for that interface. Now, how about the shortcut

00:14:13.639 --> 00:14:18.730
version of the command? Well, as you can see,
there are many possible commands beginning

00:14:18.730 --> 00:14:25.399
with ‘i’ from global config mode, so that’s
too short. However, there is only one option

00:14:25.399 --> 00:14:31.839
beginning with ‘in’, so that’s the shortest
version of the command. Keep in mind, you

00:14:31.839 --> 00:14:36.740
don’t have to use or even remember what
the shortest version of each command is. For

00:14:36.740 --> 00:14:43.640
example I always type ‘int’ for interface,
even though ‘in’ would work too. Just

00:14:43.640 --> 00:14:48.370
use whatever is comfortable for you. It may
even help you remember the commands if you

00:14:48.370 --> 00:14:55.370
type the whole thing out every time. Okay,
now how about the short version of gigabitethernet?

00:14:55.370 --> 00:15:01.930
Well, as you can see there are multiple options
with just G, so you might think that’s too

00:15:01.930 --> 00:15:08.940
short. However, here’s something cool. If
you type the 0/0 after the G, it works! The

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:13.940
CLI will understand and bring you into
interface configuration mode for gigabitethernet

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:21.170
0/0. So, whether you prefer to use shortcuts
to maximize efficiency, or take your time

00:15:21.170 --> 00:15:25.899
and type out the whole command, remember that
the command to enter interface configuration

00:15:25.899 --> 00:15:31.190
mode is ‘interface’, followed by the interface
name.

00:15:31.190 --> 00:15:36.269
Now that we’re in interface configuration
mode, let’s set the IP address. That is

00:15:36.269 --> 00:15:42.259
done with the command IP address, and then
you type the IP address. Notice I used the

00:15:42.259 --> 00:15:47.630
context-sensitive help, the question mark,
to display the next option, and it is the

00:15:47.630 --> 00:15:53.020
‘subnet mask’. This is another name for
the ‘netmask’ I referred to in a previous

00:15:53.020 --> 00:15:59.930
video. As opposed to writing /8 for this class
A address, we will have to write out the subnet

00:15:59.930 --> 00:16:05.920
mask in dotted decimal. For those of you who
have heard of the term ‘subnet’ or ‘subnetting’

00:16:05.920 --> 00:16:12.819
before, don’t worry. We’ll cover those
topics in depth soon in separate videos. So,

00:16:12.819 --> 00:16:21.140
you may remember /8 is equivalent to 255.0.0.0.
/8 means that the first bits are all set

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:30.339
to 1, and a binary octet of all 1s is written
as 255 in decimal. Next I enter the command

00:16:30.339 --> 00:16:36.529
‘no shutdown’. This is the command we
use to enable the interface. Remember I said

00:16:36.529 --> 00:16:41.920
that Cisco router interfaces have the ‘shutdown’
command applied to them by default? Well,

00:16:41.920 --> 00:16:47.779
to cancel the command, type ‘no’ in front
of the command like this. Now that we entered

00:16:47.779 --> 00:16:53.540
the no shutdown command on the interface,
we get two messages on the device. The first

00:16:53.540 --> 00:17:01.149
one says ‘Interface gigabitethernet0/0,
changed state to up. This refers to the physical

00:17:01.149 --> 00:17:06.500
layer status of the interface, the ‘STATUS’
column of the show ip interface brief command

00:17:06.500 --> 00:17:13.140
we looked at. The second message says ‘Line
protocol on interface gigabitethernet0/0,

00:17:13.140 --> 00:17:19.230
changed state to up.’ This is the layer
2 status of the interface, the ‘protocol’

00:17:19.230 --> 00:17:26.650
column of the show ip interface brief command.
So, now if we take a look at the show ip interface

00:17:26.650 --> 00:17:34.159
brief command, both of those columns should
display up. Lets check. Here I use ‘do’

00:17:34.159 --> 00:17:39.270
to let me execute this privileged exec mode
command from interface config mode, and notice

00:17:39.270 --> 00:17:51.289
I used shortcuts instead, SH ip INT BR, instead
of show ip interface brief. As you can see,

00:17:51.289 --> 00:17:57.770
we can now see the IP address, the method
is displayed as manual instead of unset, and

00:17:57.770 --> 00:18:04.750
both the status and protocol display up. Seems
like our interface configuration was a success!

00:18:04.750 --> 00:18:10.850
Let’s do the configurations for the G0/1
interface next. I’ll give it an address

00:18:10.850 --> 00:18:21.390
of 172.16.255.254. The prefix length is /16,
so what will the subnet mask be?

00:18:21.390 --> 00:18:29.980
So, I use the int g0/1 command to enter interface
config mode for the interface. Notice that

00:18:29.980 --> 00:18:37.030
I didn’t type ‘exit’ to return to global
config mode and then type int g0/1. You can

00:18:37.030 --> 00:18:43.530
directly switch from one interface to the
other. Next I configure the IP address, using

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:51.659
the shortcut ‘add’ for address. Notice
the subnet mask of 255.255.0.0, which indicates

00:18:51.659 --> 00:18:58.870
a prefix length of /16. Then I enable the
interface with ‘no shut’, which is a short

00:18:58.870 --> 00:19:05.710
version of the no shutdown command. Once again,
I get two messages saying the interface has

00:19:05.710 --> 00:19:12.360
come up. Then I check the interfaces again
with show ip interface brief, and you can

00:19:12.360 --> 00:19:19.110
see that gigabitethernet0/1 has an IP address,
and its status is UP UP.

00:19:19.110 --> 00:19:29.760
Finally, let’s configure R1’s g0/2 interface
with an IP address of 192.168.0.254. The prefix

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:34.890
length is /24, so what do you think the subnet
mask will be?

00:19:34.890 --> 00:19:43.700
So, I use ‘int g0/2’ to enter interface
config mode for gigabitethernet 0/2. Then

00:19:43.700 --> 00:19:54.340
I configure an IP address of 192.168.0.254,
and the subnet mask is 255.255.255.0, which

00:19:54.340 --> 00:20:01.861
is equivalent to a prefix length of /24. I
enable the interface with ‘no shut’, and once

00:20:01.861 --> 00:20:07.520
again I get the two messages indicating the
interface has come up, and then once more

00:20:07.520 --> 00:20:13.360
I check the status of the interfaces with
show ip interface brief. Looks like all of

00:20:13.360 --> 00:20:19.100
the interfaces have been properly configured.
Their IP addresses are displayed, their method

00:20:19.100 --> 00:20:24.910
column displays ‘manual’, since I manually
configured their IP addresses, and their status

00:20:24.910 --> 00:20:31.740
and protocol columns show up and up. Before
finishing, I want to introduce some more

00:20:31.740 --> 00:20:38.240
‘show’ commands that can be used to check
out the interfaces on a Cisco device.

00:20:38.240 --> 00:20:44.669
First up is the ‘show interfaces’ command.
You can enter just ‘show interfaces’,

00:20:44.669 --> 00:20:49.659
but it shows a lot of information for each
interface, so I recommend specifying which

00:20:49.659 --> 00:20:56.880
interface you want to check, in this case
I specified G0/0. This command shows primarily

00:20:56.880 --> 00:21:04.690
Layer 1 and Layer 2 information about the
interface, but also some Layer 3. Gigabitethernet0/0

00:21:04.690 --> 00:21:11.779
is up, that means that Layer 1 is working.
Line protocol is up, that refers to the Layer

00:21:11.779 --> 00:21:18.030
2 status of the interface. This line is like
the status and protocol columns of the ‘show

00:21:18.030 --> 00:21:26.179
ip interface brief’ command. Hardware is
1GBE, meaning 1 gigabit ethernet, address

00:21:26.179 --> 00:21:38.450
is 0c1b.8444.f000. That’s the MAC address
of this interface. Notice it says BIA, followed

00:21:38.450 --> 00:21:43.960
by the MAC address again. I mentioned in a
previous video that the MAC address can also

00:21:43.960 --> 00:21:51.860
be called the burned in address. Well, thats
what BIA stands for. Why is it listed twice?

00:21:51.860 --> 00:21:58.140
Well, BIA refers to the actual physical address
of the interface. However, you can actually

00:21:58.140 --> 00:22:03.610
configure a different MAC address in the CLI,
although usually you won’t configure a different

00:22:03.610 --> 00:22:15.200
MAC address. Internet address is 10.255.255.254/8.
This is the IP address, of course. Feel free

00:22:15.200 --> 00:22:19.490
to take a look at the rest of this information
if you want, but I’ll explain more of it

00:22:19.490 --> 00:22:25.690
in detail in a later video. It’s all detailed
Layer 1 and Layer 2 information about the

00:22:25.690 --> 00:22:27.690
interface.

00:22:27.690 --> 00:22:33.909
Now let’s look at one more valuable command.
‘show interfaces description’. Well, as

00:22:33.909 --> 00:22:40.100
you can see it has status and protocol columns
like the show ip interface brief command.

00:22:40.100 --> 00:22:45.820
But it also has this ‘description’ column.
Interface descriptions are optional, but can

00:22:45.820 --> 00:22:51.159
be very helpful in identifying the purpose
of each interface. Let’s quickly go back

00:22:51.159 --> 00:22:54.750
and configure descriptions on each of these
interfaces.

00:22:54.750 --> 00:23:02.480
So, from global config mode I once again entered
interface config mode for G0/0. The command

00:23:02.480 --> 00:23:08.040
to configure an interface description is simply
‘description’, followed by the description.

00:23:08.040 --> 00:23:14.820
Now, there aren’t any rules regarding how
to describe your interfaces. I use hashtags

00:23:14.820 --> 00:23:19.659
to make the descriptions more noticeable,
and then I indicate which device the interface

00:23:19.659 --> 00:23:28.640
is connected to. I do the same for G0/1 and
G0/2, using ‘D E S C’ instead of the full

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:35.350
description command. I then use the show interfaces
description command again, and now you can

00:23:35.350 --> 00:23:40.919
see the description of each interface. Now,
there are many more ‘show’ commands you

00:23:40.919 --> 00:23:46.920
can use to obtain information about a device’s
interfaces. We’ll take a look at a few more

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:53.850
throughout this course, but for now remember
‘show ip interface brief’, ‘show interfaces’,

00:23:53.850 --> 00:23:57.309
and ‘show interfaces description’.

00:23:57.309 --> 00:24:01.700
Now let’s review what we covered. This is
the same slide I showed at the beginning of

00:24:01.700 --> 00:24:07.700
the video, but let’s go through and make
sure we covered everything. We covered IPv4

00:24:07.700 --> 00:24:13.690
address classes, which we also covered in
Part 1, but reviewed in this video. We talked

00:24:13.690 --> 00:24:20.191
about how to find the maximum number of hosts,
network address, broadcast address, first

00:24:20.191 --> 00:24:25.880
usable address, and last usable address of
a particular network. If you’re not sure

00:24:25.880 --> 00:24:30.460
about any of those, go back and listen to
that part of the video once more before moving

00:24:30.460 --> 00:24:37.450
on to today’s quiz. Finally, I showed you
how to configure IP addresses on Cisco devices,

00:24:37.450 --> 00:24:43.120
as well as some ‘show’ commands to gather
information about interfaces.

00:24:43.120 --> 00:24:47.669
Now let’s go on to the quiz for today’s
video. If you want further help remembering

00:24:47.669 --> 00:24:52.019
what you’ve studied, remember to download
and use the Anki flashcards from the link

00:24:52.019 --> 00:24:58.320
in the description. For this quiz, I’ll
focus on finding the maximum number of hosts,

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:05.730
network address, broadcast address, and first
and last usable addresses of a network.

00:25:05.730 --> 00:25:17.890
First up, question 1: PC1 has an IP address of 43.109.23.12/8.
Find the following: The network address, the

00:25:17.890 --> 00:25:23.039
maximum number of hosts in the network, the
network broadcast address, the first usable

00:25:23.039 --> 00:25:28.230
address of the network, and the last usable
address of the network. Pause the video to

00:25:28.230 --> 00:25:39.799
find the answers.  Okay, let’s
check. The network address is 43.0.0.0, since

00:25:39.799 --> 00:25:50.140
only the first octet is the network portion.
The maximum number of hosts is 16,777,214,

00:25:50.140 --> 00:25:56.500
which is 2 to the power of 24, because there
are 24 host bits in the network, minus 2,

00:25:56.500 --> 00:26:04.360
for the network and broadcast addresses. The
first usable address is 43.0.0.1, which is

00:26:04.360 --> 00:26:12.960
the network address plus 1, and then the last
usable address is 43.255.255.254, which is

00:26:12.960 --> 00:26:18.080
the broadcast address minus 1. Let’s go
to question 2.

00:26:18.080 --> 00:26:29.120
PC4 has an IP address of 129.221.23.13/16.
Find the same five values. Pause the video

00:26:29.120 --> 00:26:41.799
to find the answer.  Okay,
so the network address is 129.221.0.0. The

00:26:41.799 --> 00:26:50.600
maximum number of hosts is 65,534, which is
2 to the power of 16, minus 2. The network

00:26:50.600 --> 00:27:01.780
broadcast address is 129.221.255.255. The
first usable address is 129.221.0.1, and the

00:27:01.780 --> 00:27:10.450
last usable address is 129.221.255.254. Let’s
go to question 3.

00:27:10.450 --> 00:27:21.710
PC8 has an IP address of 209.211.3.22/24 Find
the same five values. Pause the video to find

00:27:21.710 --> 00:27:32.420
the answer.  Okay, so the
network address is 209.211.3.0. The maximum

00:27:32.420 --> 00:27:39.350
number of hosts is 254, which is 2 to the
power of 8, minus 2. The network broadcast

00:27:39.350 --> 00:27:50.360
address is 209.211.3.255. The first usable
address is 209.211.3.1, and the last usable

00:27:50.360 --> 00:27:58.340
address is 209.211.3.254. Let’s go to question
4.

00:27:58.340 --> 00:28:10.309
PC5 has an IP address of 2.71.209.233/8 Find
the same five values. Pause the video to find

00:28:10.309 --> 00:28:21.240
the answer.  Okay, so the
network address is 2.0.0.0 The maximum number

00:28:21.240 --> 00:28:33.029
of hosts is 16,777,214, which is 2 to the
power of 24, minus 2. The network broadcast

00:28:33.029 --> 00:28:43.639
address is 2.255.255.255. The first usable
address is 2.0.0.1, and the last usable address

00:28:43.639 --> 00:28:51.269
is 2.255.255.254. Let’s go to question 5.

00:28:51.269 --> 00:29:04.559
PC6 has an IP address of 155.200.201.141/16
Find the same five values. Pause the video

00:29:04.559 --> 00:29:16.580
to find the answer.  Okay,
so the network address is 155.200.0.0 The

00:29:16.580 --> 00:29:25.690
maximum number of hosts is 65,534 which is
2 to the power of 16, minus 2. The network

00:29:25.690 --> 00:29:37.250
broadcast address is 155.200.255.255. The
first usable address is 155.200.0.1, and the

00:29:37.250 --> 00:29:43.200
last usable address is 155.200.255.254.

00:29:43.280 --> 00:29:49.500
Okay, that’s all for the quiz. Hopefully
you feel confident in determining the network

00:29:49.510 --> 00:29:55.440
address, maximum hosts, broadcast address,
and the first and last usable addresses of

